Known North American localities of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peck &amp; Cook" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Crotch" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[712,1014,1905,1928]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Macrohydnobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matthewsii">
<emphasis box="[712,1014,1905,1928]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Macrohydnobius matthewsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(black dots) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peck &amp; Cook" authorityYear="2009" box="[1198,1369,1905,1928]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Macrohydnobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tibiocalcaris">
<emphasis box="[1198,1369,1905,1928]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">M. tibiocalcaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(open square).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="39.[151,1436,151,835]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,464,151,177]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Nomenclatural notes.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[471,719,152,177]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Agathidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallidum">
<emphasis box="[471,719,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Agathidium pallidum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described by Thomas 
<bibRefCitation author="Say, T." box="[1034,1210,152,178]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" pagination="83 - 99" refId="ref30837" refString="Say, T. (1824) Descriptions of Coleopterous Insects collected in the late Expedition to the Rocky Mountains, performed by order of Mr. Calhoun, Secretary of War, under the command of Major Long. Journal of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, 4, 83 - 99." type="journal article" year="1824">Say (1824: 91)</bibRefCitation>
. The specimen was subsequently lost or destroyed (
<bibRefCitation author="Ord, G." box="[530,648,190,216]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" pagination="vi - xxi" refId="ref30577" refString="Ord, G. (1859) A memoir of Thomas Say. In: LeConte, J. L. (Ed.), The complete writings of Thomas Say on the entomology of North America, Vol 1. Bailliere Brothers, New York, pp vi - xxi." type="book chapter" year="1859">Ord 1859</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Mawdsley, J." box="[661,856,190,216]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" pagination="163 - 171" refId="ref30255" refString="Mawdsley, J. (1993). The entomological collection of Thomas Say. Psyche, 100, 163 - 171." type="journal article" year="1993">Mawdsley 1993</bibRefCitation>
). The name has been associated with 
<taxonomicName authority="Crotch. Horn (1880: 281)" authorityName="Crotch. Horn" authorityPageNumber="281" authorityYear="1880" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Hydnobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matthewsii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Hydnobius matthewsii</emphasis>
Crotch. 
<bibRefCitation author="Horn, G. H." box="[382,591,229,255]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" pagination="219 - 322" refId="ref29843" refString="Horn, G. H. (1880) Synopsis of the Silphidae of the United States with reference to the genera of other countries. Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 8, 219 - 322." type="journal article" year="1880">Horn (1880: 281)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
states that it “may be this species” under his account of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crotch. Horn" authorityYear="1880" box="[1264,1429,229,254]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Hydnobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matthewsii">
<emphasis box="[1264,1429,229,254]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">H. matthewsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The name was associated with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crotch. Horn" authorityYear="1880" box="[539,710,268,293]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Hydnobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matthewsii">
<emphasis box="[539,710,268,293]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">H. matthewsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hatch, M. H." box="[760,971,268,294]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" refId="ref29710" refString="Hatch, M. H. (1929) Coleopterorum Catalogus: Leiodidae, Clambidae. Pars 105. W. Junk, Berlin, 99 pp." type="book" year="1929">Hatch (1929: 11)</bibRefCitation>
as “? 
<taxonomicName authority="Say" authorityName="Say" box="[1051,1221,268,294]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Agathidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallidum">
<emphasis box="[1051,1160,268,293]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">pallidum</emphasis>
Say
</taxonomicName>
”. Based on Say’s sufficiently clear description we can determine that the specimen was not 
<taxonomicName authority="(Crotch)" authorityName="Peck &amp; Cook" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Crotch" baseAuthorityYear="1874" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Macrohydnobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matthewsii">
<emphasis box="[1084,1436,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Macrohydnobius matthewsii</emphasis>
(Crotch)
</taxonomicName>
and we are unable to place it within the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lopatin" authorityYear="1961" box="[724,815,345,371]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Sogdini">Sogdini</taxonomicName>
and assume it is in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1838" box="[1089,1227,345,371]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Agathidiini">Agathidiini</taxonomicName>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[1290,1341,345,371]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">type</typeStatus>
locality was stated as “Engineer Cantonment” which was the winter encampment of the 1819–20 expedition, led by 
<taxonomicName authority="Stephen H. Long" box="[151,453,422,448]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="major">Major Stephen H. Long</taxonomicName>
, to explore the southern Rocky Mountains (
<bibRefCitation author="Beidleman, R. G." box="[1009,1222,422,448]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" pagination="307 - 313" refId="ref29326" refString="Beidleman, R. G. (1986) The 1820 Long Expedition. American Zoologist, 26, 307 - 313." type="journal article" year="1986">Beidleman 1986</bibRefCitation>
). Archaeological investigation by the 
<collectingRegion box="[389,565,461,487]" country="United States of America" name="Nebraska" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Nebraska State</collectingRegion>
Historical Society has established the site of the encampment on the bank of the 
<collectingRegion box="[226,330,500,526]" country="United States of America" name="Missouri" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Missouri</collectingRegion>
River, a few miles north of present-day Omaha (
<bibRefCitation author="Carlson, G. F. &amp; Bozell, J. R. &amp; Pepperl, R." box="[903,1133,500,526]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" refId="ref29413" refString="Carlson, G. F., Bozell, J. R. &amp; Pepperl, R. (2004) The search for Engineer Cantonment. Explore Nebraska Archeology No. 8. Nebraska State Historical Society, Lincoln, Nebraska, 31 pp." type="book" year="2004">
Carlson 
<emphasis box="[1003,1055,500,525]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">et al</emphasis>
. 2004
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="39" pageNumber="40" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="39.[151,1436,151,835]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,359,538,564]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Distribution.</emphasis>
The species occurs in forested northwestern North America and to the east to Wyoming (
<figureCitation box="[160,267,577,603]" captionStart="FIGURE 107" captionStartId="38.[151,254,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[228,1360,1226,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-91@38.[228,1360,1226,1878]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 107. Known North American localities of Macrohydnobius matthewsii (black dots) and M. tibiocalcaris (open square)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310959" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310959/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Fig. 107</figureCitation>
). We have seen specimens from 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[668,778,576,602]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
<collectingCountry box="[668,773,576,602]" name="Canada" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Canada</collectingCountry>
:
</emphasis>
the province of 
<collectingRegion box="[982,1197,577,603]" country="Canada" name="British Columbia" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">British Columbia</collectingRegion>
; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1210,1280,576,602]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
<collectingCountry box="[1210,1274,576,602]" name="United States of America" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">USA</collectingCountry>
:
</emphasis>
the states of 
<collectingRegion box="[151,273,616,642]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">California</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[284,354,616,642]" country="United States of America" name="Idaho" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Idaho</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[366,473,616,642]" country="United States of America" name="Montana" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Montana</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[484,575,616,642]" country="United States of America" name="Oregon" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Oregon</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[587,729,616,642]" country="United States of America" name="Washington" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Washington</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion box="[790,909,616,642]" country="United States of America" name="Wyoming" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Wyoming</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="39.[151,1436,151,835]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,518,654,680]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Field notes and habitats.</emphasis>
Adults have been collected most frequently on snow, with a few in flight intercept and pitfall traps, with eight in pitfall traps in sand dunes, five on hypogeous 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vittadini" authorityYear="1831" box="[1151,1265,693,718]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Gomphaceae" genus="Gautieria" kingdom="Fungi" order="Gomphales" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1151,1265,693,718]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Gautieria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fungi and five on 
<taxonomicName box="[187,327,732,757]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Rhizopogonaceae" genus="Rhizopogon" kingdom="Fungi" order="Boletales" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[187,327,732,757]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Rhizopogon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fungi.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="39.[151,1436,151,835]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,346,770,796]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Seasonality.</emphasis>
Adults have been collected from August to January, with the exception of one in June. The greatest numbers are for October (32), November (113), and December (21).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
